sodium-potassium ATPase on the basolateral membrane","Active transport via sodium-potassium ATPase on the luminal membrane","Sodium-hydrogen exchange on the basolateral membrane","Active transport via sodium channels independent of other ions"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct mechanism involves \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium-hydrogen exchange on the luminal membrane coupled with sodium-potassium ATPase on the basolateral membrane\u003C/strong\u003E. Sodium enters the proximal tubule cell from the lumen via the sodium-hydrogen exchanger (NHE3), driven by the concentration gradient maintained by the sodium-potassium ATPase pump on the basolateral membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPassive diffusion through tight junctions\u003C/strong\u003E accounts for a small proportion of sodium reabsorption in the proximal tubule, occurring after transcellular transport creates a concentration gradient\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport via sodium-potassium ATPase on the luminal membrane\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as this pump is exclusively located on the basolateral membrane to maintain the sodium gradient\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium-hydrogen exchange on the basolateral membrane\u003C/strong\u003E would not allow for efficient sodium reabsorption as it would move sodium back into the tubular lumen\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport via sodium channels independent of other ions\u003C/strong\u003E does not occur in the proximal tubule - sodium transport is always coupled to other ions or solutes\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis mechanism allows for efficient sodium reabsorption while also facilitating the transport of other substances like glucose and amino acids through secondary active transport processes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The proximal tubule reabsorbs approximately 65% of filtered sodium and water through both transcellular and paracellular pathways.","The luminal sodium-hydrogen exchanger together with the basal sodium-potassium ATPase are the primary drivers of sodium reabsorption in the proximal tubule","The proximal tubule maintains glomerulotubular balance by adjusting reabsorption based on filtered load."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65971"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17686"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65971"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T09:11:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T09:12:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10400"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80675"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"rela